definition.value: A piperidine compound having a (2-thienyl)ethyl substituent at the 1-position, a methyl group at the 3-position and an N-phenylpropanamido group at the 4-position.
The (R)-enantiomer of 3-methylthiofentanyl.
The (S)-enantiomer of 3-methylthiofentanyl.
A hydroxycoumarin that is warfarin in which the hydrogen at position 4 of the phenyl substituent is replaced by a nitro group.
An  organic sodium salt derivative of toluene-4-sulfonamide with a chloro substituent in place of an amino hydrogen.
The (R)-enantiomer of acenocoumarol.
The (R)-enantiomer of acenocoumarol.
A phenothiazine compound having an acetyl group at the 2-position and a 2-(dimethylamino)-1-propyl group at the 10-position.
The (R)-enantiomer of aceprometazine.
The (S)-enantiomer of aceprometazine.
A cardenolide glycoside compound consisting of digitoxin having an acetyl substituent at the 3-position on the D-ribo-hexopyranosyl residue at the non-reducing end.
A poly(ethylene glycol) derivative that is poly(ethylene glycol) in which one of the terminal hydroxy groups has been converted into the corresponding p-nonylphenyl ether.
A tergitol polymer consisting of nonylbenzene with a nine-membered poly(ethylene glycol) moiety attached at position 4.
A prednisolone compound having an alpha-chloro substituent at the 7-position and an alpha-methyl substituent at the 16-position.
The hemifumarate salt of aliskiren.
A triamino-1,3,5-triazine compound having allylamino substituents at the 2- and 4-positions and a 4-(bis(p-fluorophenyl)methyl)-1-piperazinyl group at the 6-position.
The dimethanesulfonate salt of almitrine.
An acrylate macromolecule composed of repeating methoxycarbonylethylene units.
The malate salt of almotriptan.
Toluene-p-sulfonamide chlorinated at nitrogen.
The hydrochloride salt of alosetron.
A drug that suppresses spasms. These are usually caused by smooth muscle contraction, especially in tubular organs. The effect is to prevent spasms of the stomach, intestine or urinary bladder.

The citrate salt of alverine, resulting from the reaction of equimolar amounts of alvarine and citric acid. An antispasmodic that acts directly on intestinal and uterine smooth muscle, it is used in the treatment of irritable bowel syndrome.
The hydrochloride salt of alverine.
The (3R)-enantiomer of aminoglutethimide.
The (3R)-enantiomer of aminoglutethimide.
Any alkaloid with a phenanthrene skeleton.
An organic heterotricyclic compound composed of a pyridine ring fused to a chromene.
A univalent carboacyl group formed by loss of OH from the carboxy group of (4-hydroxy-3-nitrophenyl)acetic acid.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of (4-hydroxy-3-nitrophenyl)acetic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
The (4R)-enantiomer of amlodipine.
The (4S)-enantiomer of amlodipine.
A univalent carboacyl group formed by loss of OH from the carboxy group of (4-hydroxy-5-iodo-3-nitrophenyl)acetic acid.
A member of the class of phenylacetic acids that is phenylacetic acid in which the phenyl group is substituted by iodo, hydroxy and nitro groups at positions 3, 4 and 5 respectively.
An acetate derivative carrying a 4-hydroxy-5-iodo-3-nitrophenyl substituent at C-2.
A trihydroxyflavone that is  galangin substituted by a prenyl  group at position 8.
A medium-chain fatty acid anion comprising hexanoate substituted at C-2 and C-4 with oxo and hydroxy groups respectively.
An organic heterotricyclic compound consisting of two benzene rings fused to a seven-membered ring containing one oxygen and one nitrogen atom.
A macromolecule in which the substituents are placed randomly along the backbone.
A polymer in which all the substituents are located on the same side of the backbone.
A macromolecule in which the substituents are located on alternate sides of the backbone
An isocyanate composed of a benzene ring bearing a single isocyanato substituent.
A trihydroxyflavanone that is (2S)-flavanone substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3, 5 and 7 and a prenyl group at position 8 respectively.

An N-sulfonylurea that is glyburide in which the (5-chloro-2-methoxybenzoyl group is replaced by a (5-methylpyrazin-2-yl)carbonyl group. An oral hypoglycemic agent, it is used in the treatment of type 2 diabetes mellitus.
A pyrazinoindole with a disulfide bridge spanning a dioxo-substituted pyrazine ring; mycotoxin produced by several species of fungi.
